title: Xi Jinping conducting military purge to potentially make army ‘ready to fight a war over Taiwan’
description: Council on Foreign Relations’ Joseph Torigian discusses China’s purge of military officials.  “I think that Xi Jinping is doing these purges in part because he believes that they’re necessary to make the People’s Liberation Army ready to fight a war over Taiwan,” he told Sky News Australia.  “At the same time, it’s hard to imagine that these purges, at least for now, are not negatively affecting military readiness.”

title: ‘Trump is not happy’: Kristi Noem faces growing pressure after Minneapolis shooting
description: Former White House chief of staff Mick Mulvaney highlights the importance of White House Border Czar Tom Homan’s shift to Immigration and Customs Enforcement operations in Minnesota.  “The administration has been getting pounded on its handling of the Minneapolis situation,” Mr Mulvaney told Sky News Australia.  “Donald Trump is not happy with the way things are running.”  Warning: Distressing footage.

title: CNN guest wildly claims ICE detention facilities are 'concentration camps' in unhinged rant
description: An unhinged CNN guest has wildly compared Immigration & Customs Enforcement (ICE) detention centres to “concentration camps”.  Last Friday, co-owner of Moon Palace Books Jamie Schwesnedl appeared on CNN’s ‘The Lead with Jake Tapper’ for an interview.  During Schwesnedl’s interview, he explained that the decision for business owners to close their doors comes as the city is being “invaded by masked gunmen”.  The business co-owner argued ICE agents were kidnapping neighbours and friends and were being transported to “concentration camps”.  Tapper pushed back on the guest’s claim, asserting he was not arguing with him, but that the term “concentration camp” was wrong to use.

title: ‘He would do it well’: Kevin Rudd to potentially run for UN Secretary-General role
description: Australian Financial Review Political Editor Phil Coorey weighs in on Kevin Rudd potentially running for the UN secretary-general role, claiming he would “do it well”.

title: ‘Huge foreign policy feat’: Leavitt touts the return of the last Israeli hostage remains
description: White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt has relayed President Trump’s announcement that the remains of the last hostage have been sent from Gaza to Israel.  Leavitt called the return for the remains a “huge foreign policy feat” for the Trump administration.  The press secretary boasted that Trump “made the impossible possible”.  Leavitt finished by saying 20 new countries have signed up to be on Trump’s “Board of Peace”, which is expected to oversee the rebuilding of Gaza.  Trump also referenced the return of the last hostage on Truth Social, congratulating his team.

title: ‘Fighting like cats in a bag’: Coalition walks into Albanese’s ‘bear trap’
description: Herald Sun Associate Editor James Campbell claims the Coalition split after walking into Albanese’s “bear trap”.   “All summer the Prime Minister has been walking around, constructing a thing with a big sign saying bear trap,” Mr Campbell told Sky News Australia.  “The former Coalition managed to walk into it.  "Now he’s got One Nation, he’s got the National Party, and he’s got the Liberal Party all fighting like cats in a bag.”

title: ‘Regime’s very weak’: Ayatollah Khamenei retreats to underground bunker over fear of US strikes
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada discusses reports of Iran’s Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei now hiding out in a bunker out of fear of being taken out by US airstrikes.  “He’s worried, regime’s very weak with those protests and that’s probably why he’s finding himself in a bunker,” she told Sky News host Peta Credlin.

title: ‘Something is amuck’: ‘Significant’ shake-up of Chinese military
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada discusses Chinese President Xi Jinping’s purge of his closest military ally, General Zhang Youxia, who is now under investigation.  “It is significant,” she told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “Definitely something is amuck.”

title: ‘Hanson’s special sauce’: One Nation outshining Liberals on anti-immigration
description: Herald Sun Associate Editor James Campbell says anti-immigration is One Nation’s “core strength”.  “That is Pauline Hanson’s special sauce, it’s not the Liberal Party’s,” Mr Campbell told Sky News Australia.  “If the Liberals want to talk about that, why wouldn’t people think; no, I want the real deal, give me the real deal.”

title: Hamas finally returns the remains of the last Israeli hostage
description: Israel has confirmed the recovery of the remains of Ran Gvili, the last Israeli hostage held in Gaza by Hamas.   This development marks a significant milestone, as it fulfils a key condition of the peace deal negotiated months ago, which required Hamas to hand over all hostages.   With all hostages now returned, the focus shifts to the next phase, which could involve the opening of the Rafah crossing for pedestrian traffic.

title: ‘Lost for words’: Tim Walz brutally blasted over ‘bizarre and offensive’ ICE comparison
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond has blasted Minnesota Governor Tim Walz over one of the most “bizarre and offensive” comparisons of the ICE raids.  “Tim Walz ... makes one of the most bizarre and offensive comparisons between what ICE is doing in Minnesota, which is rounding up and trying to deport illegal immigrants, to Anne Frank,” he said.  “I’m honestly lost for words – how with a straight face do you make that comparison?”

title: At least nine dingoes euthanised after fatal attack on K’gari Island
description: At least nine of the 10 dingoes involved in the fatal attack on a Canadian backpacker on K’gari Island have been euthanised by the Queensland government.  The traditional owners of K’gari are considering legal action, claiming they were not consulted about the major cull.  The state government has refused to explain the decision and announced increased range patrols in the coming weeks.  Additionally, plans are underway to construct bridges on the island.

title: One Nation surge will ‘drift back’ to Liberals over the economy
description: Herald Sun Associate Editor James Campbell claims One Nation’s surge will "drift back" to the Liberal Party over the economy.  “Anti-immigration is a core One Nation strength,” Mr Campbell told Sky News Australia.  “If and when the political discussion moves back onto the economy, I think you’re going to see a drift back from One Nation to the Liberal Party.”

title: Northern Territory introduces mandatory national anthem policy
description: The Northern Territory government has announced a new policy making it mandatory for students to sing the national anthem at school assemblies.  The move aims to instil national pride, but has drawn mixed reactions, with some questioning whether academic performance should be the priority over such issues.  The inclusion of the second verse has also sparked controversy.

title: ‘Division won’t work’: Coalition has ‘moral obligation’ to come together
description: Shadow Immigration Minister Paul Scarr claims the Nationals and Liberals have a “moral obligation” to come together.  “I’ve seen first hand what division on the non-Labor side of politics causes,” Mr Scarr told Sky News Australia.  “That’s one of the reasons we came together because division on the non-Labor side of politics does not work.”
